US Best Low Cost Vacation Destinations¶

Team 4, Cohrent A

Luke Towers, Yanyue Fu, Ke Zang, Mandi Zhu, Yue Wu

2019/08/19

Introduction¶

We are analysing Air Bnb data for a low income family that have decided they want to travel within the US. They are a family of 4 who do not want to share rooms. They also do not want strict cancelation fee's in case they want to cancel last minute. They want to save as much money as possible but they want the best experience they can.

Following are a few questions that we aim to answer through our analysis:¶

  1. How many records are there in this airbnb dataset?
  2. How cancelation policy would affect the average price of an Air Bnb?
  3. Are hosts reponse time and the price of an Air Bnb correlated?
  4. Will the popularity affect price of an Air Bnb?
  5. What is the most common room type in US Air Bnb?
  6. Do different types of room have different average price?
  7. Which US cities have the highest average rating?
  8. What is the distrubution of Air Bnb in each city??
  9. How does average price of Air Bnb vary among cities? And choose two cities based on the average reviewing scores and avereage price.
  10. Analyze the first city by adding the filter review_scores_rating
  11. Analyze the first city by adding the filter review_scores_rating, number of accomadates and room type
  12. Analyze the first city by adding the filter review_scores_rating, number of accomadates,room type and cancellation policy
  13. Analyze the second city by adding the filter review_scores_rating
  14. Analyze the second city by adding the filter review_scores_rating, number of accomadates and room type
  15. Analyze the second city by adding the filter review_scores_rating, number of accomadates,room type and cancellation policy
  16. Compare two cities and make final decision for the family
  17. Some suggestions for travelling with low AirBnb charge.

Description of Data¶

The data that we have decided to use is Air Bnb listin data from major cities in the US. These cities include San Francisco, New York City, Chicargo, Boston, Los Angeles and Washington DC. The data includes the following fields:

id - The identifyer of each data point

Log_Price - This is the natural log of the price per night of the accomodation.

Property_type - This is the kind of property it is e.g. House or apartment.

Room_type - This is the kind of room inside the accomodation e.g. Shared or private.

Accommodates - This is the number of people the property accommodates.

Bathrooms - This is the number of bathrooms in the property.

Bed_type - This is the type of bed e.g. Real bed or futon.

cancellation_policy - This is the owners policy on cancellations e.g. Strict/moderate/flexible.

Cleaning_fee - This is whether the owner charges a cleaning fee.

City - The location of the property.

First_review - This is the date of the first review of the property.

Host has profile pic - Whether the owner has a prfile pictire on file.

host_identity_verfication - This is whether the host has been verified by air bnb.

Host response rate - This is the response rate in percentage for each listing.

Instant_bookable - This is showing if you can book instantly through the app or website.

last_review - This is showing the date of last review of each listing.

Lat / Long - This is showing the coordinated of the listing.

Number of reviews - This is showing how many times the listing was reviewed.

Review score rating - Shows the average rating of each property out of 100.

Zipcode - Shows the zipcode of the listing.

Bedrooms - Shows the number of bedrooms of the listing.

Beds - Shows the number of beds in the listing.

Price - Shows the price per night.

Q1: How many records are there in this airbnb dataset?¶

(1) The raw dataset's link: https://www.kaggle.com/rudymizrahi/airbnb-listings-in-major-us-cities-deloitte-ml

In [ ]:
%%bq query
select * from `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_row_data`

(2) Firstly, add the 'normal price' to the table.

In [ ]:
%%bq query
create or replace table `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final`
as
SELECT *, POWER(2.718, log_price) as price
FROM `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_row_data`

(3) Secondly, clean all NULL/NA in raw data.

In [ ]:
%%bq query
DELETE FROM `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final` 
where (log_price is null) or property_type is null or room_type is null or accommodates is null or bathrooms is null or bed_type is null or cancellation_policy is null or cleaning_fee is null or city is null or host_response_rate is null or instant_bookable is null or last_review is null or latitude is null or longitude is null or number_of_reviews is null or review_scores_rating is null or zipcode is null or bedrooms is null or beds is null or price is null

Q2:How cancelation policy would affect the average price of an Air Bnb?¶

We wanted to start by doing some exploratory queries to understand more about our data before we tackle our main case involving our family. We began by finding out how cancelation policy would affect the average price of an Air Bnb. From this we can see that the more flexible with cancelations the cheaper the price usually is.

In [58]:
%%bq query 
SELECT cancellation_policy, round(avg(price),1) AS avg_price,
case when avg(price) >= 174 then "Expensive"
     when avg(price) >= 110 then "Moderate"
     else "Cheap"
end as Price_classification
FROM `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final`
group by cancellation_policy
ORDER BY avg_price;
Out[58]:
cancellation_policyavg_pricePrice_classification
flexible114.9Moderate
moderate133.6Moderate
strict169.0Moderate
super_strict_30263.3Expensive
super_strict_60641.1Expensive

(rows: 5, time: 0.9s, 802KB processed, job: job_cIKA-88vkZ7dXEAqWEvtc6BVCHOn)

Q3: Are hosts reponse time and the price of an Air Bnb correlated?¶

We decided to see if there was a correlation between the hosts response time and the price of an Air Bnb. From these results we generated a scatter plot to visulize the relationship. We can see that there is a very slight positive correlation. As the response rate increases the average price also very slightly increases. We can also see from the chart there are some outliers probably coming from small amounts of data at certain response rate data points.

In [59]:
%%bq query -n Response_rate
SELECT host_response_rate , avg(price) AS avg_price  FROM `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final` 
group by host_response_rate;

Q4: Will the popularity affect price of an Air Bnb?¶

Then we decided to look at how popularity affected price. We determined popularity by the number of reviews a certain accomodation has and we plotted this against price. You can see from the chart that popularity is highest at the lower prices. This makes sense when thinking about the customers using air bnb, usually trying to save money and not pay alot for hotels. This graph shows that the market for expensive air bnb listings is much smaller than cheaper listings.

In [13]:
%%bq query -n review
select  price, number_of_reviews from `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final`
order by price

Q5: What is the most common room type in US Air Bnb?¶

We also wanted to see what the most common types of rooms were amoungst Air bnbs, so we generated a pie chart to show what percentage each kind of room is. As you can see the shared room is considerably lower than all other types.

In [15]:
%%bq query -n roomtype
-- Which is the most common room type?
SELECT room_type, count(room_type) as quantity 
FROM `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final` 
group by room_type
order by count(room_type) desc;

Q6: Does different types of room have different price classification?¶

Following on price classification we can see shared room and private room are considerably cheap than Entire house/apt, and shared room is the cheapest room type among them.

In [17]:
%%bq query
SELECT room_type, round(avg(Price),1) AS avg_price,
case when round(avg(Price),1) >= 174 then "Expensive"
     when round(avg(Price),1) >= 110 then "Moderate"
     else "Cheap"
end as Price_classification
FROM `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final`
Group by room_type
Order by avg_price;

Q10: Analyze the first city by adding the filter review_scores_rating¶

After determining the two cities that we decided to analyze based on price, and rating we decided to find the lowest average price based on the zipcodes within each city. We then limit this to 3 results. We also added a constraint that makes the average rating above 90. Although the family is trying to save money, they also want to stay somwhere with good quality and safety. This first set of analysis is on the city of Chicargo.

In [18]:
%%bq query
select zipcode, round(avg(review_scores_rating),2) as average_rating, round(avg(price),1) as price
from `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final`
where city = 'Chicago' 
group by zipcode
having avg(review_scores_rating) >= 90
order by price
LIMIT 3

Q11: Analyze the first city by adding the filter review_scores_rating, number of accomadates and room type¶

Next, we added a constraint that the booking must accomodate 4 or more. This is becasue our family consist of 4 members. We also added that the room type should NOT be shared, as the members of the family would not want to be sharing a room.

In [30]:
%%bq query
select zipcode, round(avg(review_scores_rating),2) as average_rating, round(avg(price),1) as price
from `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final`
where city = 'Chicago' and accommodates >=4 and room_type != 'Shared room'
group by zipcode
having avg(review_scores_rating) >= 90

Q12: Analyze the first city by adding the filter review_scores_rating, number of accomadates, room type and cancellation policy¶

We then included the constraint on cancellation policy, this family does not want a strict cancellation policy in case they need to cancel at the last minute. (We notice that as we added a constraint on cancellation fee the average price actually went down, we belive that this is a problem with the data as in a real world situation this would not happen.) As shown below, the area with zipcode '60632' might be the best place for them. Further, we set this result as 'table_1' and we'll use it to prove our result later.

In [32]:

Still, the number of AirBnb available for customers and the number of review are two key factors for customers when they make a final decision. This table will display these two factors in each area in Chicago. This table called 'table_2'.

In [36]:
%%bq query
CREATE OR REPLACE table `team-4-249220.project_1.table_2`
as
with rating as (select review_scores_rating from `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final` where review_scores_rating >= 90)
select zipcode, count(*)as number_of_airbnb, avg(number_of_reviews) as number_of_review from `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final`
where city = "Chicago" and review_scores_rating in (select * from rating)
group by zipcode
order by count(*) desc

To double check our result in Chicago, we'll join table_1 and table_2 together. As shown below, it proves that this family should book the Airbnb in '60632' if they prefer to travel in Chicago.

In [49]:
%%bq query
SELECT A.zipcode, average_rating, price, number_of_airbnb, number_of_review 
FROM `team-4-249220.project_1.table_1` as A
left join 
`team-4-249220.project_1.table_2` as B
on A.zipcode = B.zipcode
order by price, average_rating desc, number_of_airbnb, number_of_review
limit 5

Q16: Compare two cities and make final decision for the family¶

from `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final`

Q18: Using BQML to predict the Air Bnb price in Chicago and NYC¶

(1) NYC-Model

In [66]:
%%bq query
CREATE OR REPLACE MODEL project_1.price_model_NYC
OPTIONS
   (model_type='linear_reg', labels=['price']) AS
  
WITH room_type_dummy AS (
 	SELECT
    	price AS price_room_type,
    	CASE WHEN room_type='Private room' THEN 1
         	ELSE 0 END AS private_room,
    	CASE WHEN room_type='Entire_home/apt' THEN 1
         	ELSE 0 END AS entire_home
    	FROM `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final` ),
    	
 	can_policy_dummy AS (
 	SELECT
     	price AS price_can_policy,
     	CASE WHEN cancellation_policy ='flexible' THEN 1
          	ELSE 0 END AS flexible,
     	CASE WHEN cancellation_policy ='moderate' THEN 1
          	ELSE 0 END AS moderate,
     	CASE WHEN cancellation_policy='super_strict_30' THEN 1
          	ELSE 0 END AS super_strict_30,
     	CASE WHEN cancellation_policy='super_strict_60' THEN 1
          	ELSE 0 END AS super_strict_60
     	FROM `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final`)
 
SELECT price, private_room, entire_home,flexible, moderate, super_strict_30, super_strict_60,  accommodates, latitude, longitude, number_of_reviews, review_scores_rating, bedrooms
FROM room_type_dummy, can_policy_dummy, `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final`
WHERE city='NYC'
LIMIT 47244
Out[66]:
Done

         	ELSE 0 END AS entire_home
    	FROM `team-4-249220.project_1.airbnb_last_final` ),
    	
     can_policy_dummy AS (
 	SELECT
     	price AS price_can_policy,
     	CASE WHEN cancellation_policy ='flexible' THEN 1
          	ELSE 0 END AS flexible,
     	CASE WHEN cancellation_policy ='moderate' THEN 1
          	ELSE 0 END AS moderate,

          	ELSE 0 END AS super_strict_30,
     	CASE WHEN cancellation_policy='super_strict_60' THEN 1
          	ELSE 0 END AS super_strict_60

   	accommodates, latitude, longitude, number_of_reviews, review_scores_rating, bedrooms
